25. diotetor: an extraordinary magistrate appointed in time of peril. lle held his office sor six months only, and was preceded by twenty-tour lictors with the fasces and axes. lle had associated with him a lieutenant called the Master of Horse (magister equitum), whom he usually appointed himself. As he had no colleague, and was irresponsible, his power was greater than that of the consul. impetum mori tregit: i.e. he checked Hannibal's victorious career by a policy of delay. His design was to harass Hannibal and tire him out, without risking a decisive battle. From the successful outcome of these tactics ‘Fabian policy' has become proverbial.
